In my last post I went over what classes are and why use them and as I said in my last post in part 2 I will be going over what exactly OOP is

## What is OOP?
OOP is a type of programming where you program around the thoughts of objects rather then functions.¬†There are many languages that offer OOP but none do it quite like class based languages. A class is a container for your object.¬†Every car may look different have different parts in the end each car does the same functions, you can start, stop, speed up, brake, and a lot more with a car.¬†So instead of having to code an object into our code and code different functions for each object we would use OOP.

## Principles of OOP
Abstraction, Inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation

## 1. Abstraction
When we split everything up into classes we might have a method called start, when we call the method start we don‚Äôt care if start is calling another function in the class to get the speed of how fast the car should be going, we as the user only care about the start method we don‚Äôt need to be able to access the private property of how fast the car should go.

## 2. Inheritance
Inheritance is the idea of reusing your code. With our car class we can do a thing to extend the class to a new class called truck. What this means is that we can use all the same start, stop, break, and other methods on our car class but along with that, we can also create new methods such as a method to check if the track has enough space for an item. When we call the truck class now we can call the start method even though we never added the start method but because we extend the parent class of car.

## 3. Polymorphism
This one is a bit hard to explain to you I‚Äôm just going to say google this one.

## 4. Encapsulation
This one is a also a bit hard to explain, what this is, is basically you put all your data and methods into one object. Then you hide the data in your class as you don‚Äôt want want to be able to access the data outside of the class.

.
.

.
.

.
.
Developers can just publish the web application online, ensure that it meets baseline "installability requirements", and users will be able to add the application to their home screen.
.

Why are DEVs Quitting Their Tech Jobs?

A few things I found out: 

üëãüèæ Over promising work prospects and under delivering which leads to lack of trust in management thereby leading devs to look for more fulfilling roles 

üëãüèæ It‚Äôs about feeling in control, a lot of people were made redundant, overworked and asked to work from home during the pandemic. This has given opportunity to employees to explore their options. With the booming creator economy, freelancing and remote work styles more people feel less hinged to their employers. 

üëãüèæ It‚Äôs about assessing what life is all about and looking for ways to create more balance. ‚ÄúHustle culture‚Äù doesn‚Äôt cut it anymore. 

üëãüèæ There‚Äôs no opportunity for personal development. From personal experience, I saw no real career progression within the company or outside of it. It‚Äôs important the technologies you are using in a company have transferable skillsets

üëãüèæ The culture is toxic. 

üëãüèæ And finally, it‚Äôs about the money, there are currently more tech roles than tech people to fill. And big tech companies have a habit of inflating the expected salary to gain the best talent in the market. Offers like these are often really difficult to reject given that in most scenarios devs do the same work but in this case, for more pay üí∞. 

What do you think? Do any of these resonate with you.

Hey guys, it's been a while. I hope you're all well.
Today I'm sharing an Octocat Loader that I've created using the #swiftUI framework.

I'm using the Shape protocol to create the custom 2-d Shape, and internally I've used Path to define the outline.

It has various functions like addLine/addCurve, which you can use for drawing. Instead of hard-coding the x and y points in the Shape, I'm using the midpoints of the available rect. By doing this, you can easily adjust the size depending on the frame provided.

I've used @State variables to manage the states of the line, and I'm using the withAnimation block to apply the animation accordingly.

I have added this animation to my open-sourced GitHub repository named SwiftUI-Animations.

I have been asked many times about why I share my background. It‚Äôs simple‚Ä¶there are a lot of #fostercare youth who don‚Äôt have a role model of what success looks like coming from their background. My pst shaped me and my career in tech allowed me to shape my future. 

The stem field itself is hard, but it is so rewarding. You meet amazing people on social media, the work life balance, and the control over your future is amazing. 

Coding changed my life and I hope it changes the lives of many of those who are in foster care.

TGIM!! 

There are no reasons why you shouldn‚Äôt learn to code. Learning to code even a little bit will help you with thinking through problems, helps you face tough challenges, opens a whole new word of possibilities for you, and so much more.

TGIM!! Thank God it‚Äôs Monday!

I told @maya_loves_code that I was coming back stronger and better than ever. I got to keep my word!

Why are you choosing to code or work the job that you do? Why are you choosing to go to the gym everyday even when it hurts?

I want to stay true to myself and represent possibility still. I want to show that anyone can learn how to code and be successful in their own way. Let‚Äôs get after it!

Throwback video from my time on the east coast. Happy Motivational Monday! 

You got this everyone! You‚Äôre stronger than any hardship that works against you.

PSA: LONG CAPTION!!!

Over the past few weeks I realized a needed a break. Not from Instagram itself, but more so from everything. 

In this year so far I have experienced highs and real lows that made me take inventory of my mental health. I am going to share two of the lows with you all that impacted me most. Not in a request for sympathy but rather an example of taking time to realize you are worthy of love and deserve to be happy and successful. 

I am one of the few former foster youth alumni who knew their biological parents. I‚Äôve experienced my own father and aunt say that I am worthless, not a real Revada, and that they always hated me. A couple weeks ago my own former college best friend who I called a brother tried to slander my name by projecting his own negative experiences to my friends here in Sacramento. It was also at this point I watched someone I loved lose a battle to alcoholism and depression.

So why say all this on a social media platform to strangers? 

I have never hidden the details of my life and I want to keep that transparency with you all. I like to believe that my content projects authenticity meaning I will never post something that I don‚Äôt believe in. 

I never wish ill will on others and I can offer my soul peace by forgiving them and moving on, but as I move on I will not take them with me. It‚Äôs a privilege to be a part of someone else‚Äôs life, not a right. Respect their boundaries and their happiness so they can do the same for you. 

You are worthy and deserving of love, happiness, success, and the joys of the world. Do not let your light be shut down by the toxicity of others. You deserve to be happy‚Ä¶

- Love Courtney Revada

What a gift and a pleasure to work with @shoutoutlaofficial for this interview. 

It gives a glimpse into my journey and some of my motivators that helped along the way. 

What a great journey it has been and it‚Äôs only getting started. I am not forgetting where I‚Äôm coming from, but I will always know where I‚Äôm going.

What breaks the monotony of work every day? In my field I try to spend 30 minutes learning (if possible) more about one of the library our application is using. Documentation can be dry sometimes, but always worth the read. 

How do you break up your day?

Does anyone genuinely have enough time?

People ask a lot of questions in regards to how long does it take to learn to code. And then I often hear others saying they don‚Äôt have enough time to learn how. 

Coding is about retention since your rewiring your brain on how to think, so there is no genuine right or wrong answer. It just depends on you. 

We all have 24 hours a day. We all have time to learn something new. It can be a minute, 30 minutes, 1hr, etc. But we all have some time. 

The question I pose to you is how do spend that 24 hours?

Seaquins revamped‚ú®

One of my biggest challenges during covid was to slow down. Being in Humboldt, where the beaches, trees and creeks intertwine, I was able to catch a glimpse of moments that make you stop for a split second, like the colors of a sunset reflecting on a river or the sudden flash of color on a hummingbird‚Äôs neck. I'm happy that this piece is capturing the essence of those moments even better now. 

Covid suresince en zorlandigim konulardan biri yavaslamak oldu. Humboldt gibi orman, kumsal ve derelerin icice gectigi bir bolgede vakit gecirmek, gunbatisinin dere ustundeki yansimasi veya sinekkusunun boynundaki tuylerin aniden parlamasi gibi dogasi geregi anlik olaylari gormek icin durmami sagladi. Bu isin yeni halinin boyle anlarin ozunu soyut olarak daha iyi yakalamasindan cok memnunum.

What preparation for my SANS exam currently looks like. Sitting a practice exam tomorrow üî•wish my luck ‚òòÔ∏è

I'm doing SEC530: Defensible Security Architecture and Engineering. The training has been immensely valuable to me. Will definitely be taking another course as soon as I can - I've already identified the next course I want to do!

 It sucks that they are so expensive though, especially if your company isn't investing in it for you üí∏You can trial courses for free, although you only get a preview, you still learn something and get a flavour for the content! 

SANS do run regular summits and weekly webinars with amazing speakers that provide free training.  I attended their lightning data science summit on Thursday night and they just did a summit on Industrial Control System Security and another one on Threat Intelligence üå©Ô∏èüè≠üö±

#SANS #cybersecurity  #cybersecuritytraining  #infosec #securityengineering #threatintelligence

Before I worked in security I used to read the latest research and vulnerabilities with great interest "wow, that's incredible!". Now my immediate reaction is more along the lines of "oh üí©, are we vulnerable?".

The recent supply chain attack, dependency confusion attacks and Azure SDK vulnerabilities (which could potentially be the source of a supply chain attack) have all been stories I've read in the news and now see what does behind the scenes when these stories break üë©‚Äçüíªüî•

#infosec #cybersecurity #DFIR #dependencyconfusion  #malware #zerodayexploit #microsoftexchange #infosec  #securityengineer #womenintech #womenincyber #womenincybersecurity

Trust yourself. 
Give yourself the time and space to do what you need to get done for your life story. 
Protect this space.
Be disciplined with this time.
Nobody cares about it as much as you do. 
Nobody has your vision. 
Surround yourself with those who understand and support your warrior path. Even if it might just be you for a while.

Still miles outside of my comfort zone. 
I have so much to say as life and work has been moving extremely fast. I haven't been using this platform at all as I find it blurs and adds noise to what I'm doing and  I  find it harder to do or get back to deep work. But I do love sharing moments along my journey ü¶ä

For now I'll just share a photo from the early hours of this morning as I was  studying in preparation for my #SANS exam in 29 days. My favourite area so far have been Mobile Security and network security monitoring. I think I like malware analysis and mobile centric security because of how much it impacts the general population and how close and personal  it is to us humans - everything from stalkerware to adware.

In the later part of 2021 I want to develop my my malware analysis skills so I can get involved in this arena, especially given my my passion and care for human rights. 

Today I'm also looking at deploying Zeek on the Rapberry Pi and then setting up a Amazon kinesis agent to aggregate the data and send to some data warehouse for analysis or something.. not sure yet! Not sure if I'll have time but it's something I want to do this week ü¶ä

Hope you find time to rest and play this weekend. I've found the more I prioritize exercise and down time during the week, the more charged and capable I am at sustaining my work and long term goals. This isn't always easy especially as my work priorities change and I have to ramp up fast to learn and gain the necessary understanding to do my job.

#cybersecuirty  #womenintech #foreignpolicy #humanrights #malwareanalysis  #cybercrime

Last week Iranian censors started blocking citizens from using the Signal messaging app. 

Signal responded  by supporting a proxy feature that enables Iranians to bypass this censorship block and use the app. They're asking for help from folks who can run a proxy to support them in securely routing their messages through Signal. Check how you can help here  https://t.co/CvSHg7XR5P 

It's fun and easy to set up. You need two things 1. a VM or however you want to run the proxy 2. A domain name pointing to the ip address running the proxy (i.e. ip address of your VM!) If you are trying to set this up and running into trouble, DM me and I'll see if I can help troubleshoot!

#IRanASignalProxy üôå DM me if you know anyone who needs a proxy and I will direct message you ro them the connection details ‚ù§Ô∏èü¶ä #privacy #humanrights #infosec #cybersecurity

Birthday week üéâüêàü¶ä

I had a TOIL day yesterday which means I had the day off work after being on call a good bit over xmas üéÑüöÄ

Spent yesterday riding my bike, migrating a website off #Kubernetes to #Azure functions and setting up an automated deployment pipeline with #githubactions.üå©Ô∏è üö¥‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüë©‚Äçüíª

 I have deployed hundreds of Lambdas functions (AWS equivalent of Azure functions) at work but never tried Azure functions. Azure really makes it super simple, your application *basically works out of the box. Super  impressed with their integration with Visual Studio Code and Github, made for a great development experience. ‚ö°üå©Ô∏è

It reminds me how important it for tooling to support developers and not make it so difficult to succeed. üíïüê†

This isn't to say that I succeeded straight away, there were a few gotchas and pain points I had to overcome to get it (almost) working. üî•

The automated deployments are almost working. I have setup a workflow of "jobs" that test, build, deploy and perform a health check on the Azure function code. There is one problem in the deploy job that I just can't figure out but will get there! 

#devops #azure #aws #github #womenwhocode

TLDR;  I love building on AWS and I joined an accountability group. New motto üëâ If it's not a üíØ% yes.. then it's a no.

Working with cross regional AWS Private links got me like ü§Øüòµ it's especially hard as another team owns the service I'm connecting to and every connection made needs to be "accepted" manually by them.. everytime I make a change in CDK/Cloudformation/the infrastructure list .. I may be resetting the connection which means I need to find another engineer .. in a different time zone to manually accept it again üôè fingers crossed it doesn't happen again ü§û #AWS

Our team has a 2021 goal to have everyone obtain a new AWS certification whether it be Cloud Solutions Architect or a Speciality cert like Security,  Networking or Data Science. I'm excited to get my GIAC certification (#SANS) and then move onto my AWS ones.

This week I joined an accountability group. Every Sunday we lock in our goals for the week and send them out to eachother. If we don't complete the goal by the specified date, we have to pay a fine into a pool. Whoever completes the most of their goals, gets to keep the money that  has grown in the pool. It  makes sure  you are only doing things you really care about.. which is great because I only want to live that way.. if  it's not a 100% yes .. then it's a no. #womenwhocode

Revamped my home office pad and  deployed @philipshue  lights across the house ü¶äüòç‚ú® I even synced my kitty headphones up too üéßüêà

I'm currently building  a pomodoro integration that will change the color of the lights depending on whether I'm in a 'focused' state or 'rest' state. I'll know if I'm working in  a flow or focus state if the lights emit a red glow or maybe even one of the hues that promote concentration. Rest states will emit a lovely calm blue hue üî•üåä

Pomodoro is a productivity rhythm or workflow  style that normally follows 4 x 25 min blocks of focused work with 5 mins rest between each set. Once you finish the set of 4, you take a 25 min long break and start again ‚è≥‚è±Ô∏è I heavily relied on this in my last two years of college to get shit done. I used a pomodoro timer app and once I pressed start I felt it quite easy to surrender to the process and just do it. I sometimes found myself checking how many minutes were left so now I'm excited to have my lighting represent when I can switch context üôåüåå

üéñThe day has finally come...

üèÜI‚Äôve been endorsed by Lambda School!!!

Started with Lambda after stumbling upon their details when looking at the list of Y Combinator alumni...

üê∞(Whoever said nothing productive comes from going down an internet rabbit-hole is a goddamn liar)

üîÜMy stumbling upon Lambda came at a perfect time for me, when I was experiencing a perfect storm:

üî∏Business imploded due to local economy suffering redundancies
üî∏Feeling hopeless and my mental health was really, really bad.
üî∏Knowing I needed to make a change.
üî∏Very narrow escape from bankruptcy and losing our house.

So I was brave enough to go for it, mostly due to the fact I had enough with the poor attitude towards teachers, and creatives, in the UK as a whole.

You‚Äôre expected to be highly highly skilled, and you‚Äôre also expected to be grateful for constant stress to just scrape by a living.

üîπI should also say thank you for my husband, who didn‚Äôt put up any objections when I said I was going to nose-dive into a sector I had no experience in, via a company no-one had ever heard of.

üò¨ I started Lambda School on the back-foot; I started when my mental health wasn‚Äôt good at all. 

‚òïÔ∏è But they stood by me; even paid for 6 weeks of therapy for me.  How many schools would do that for you?üôè

üîâDon‚Äôt get me wrong, Lambda isn‚Äôt perfect.  But I know in my heart the people who are there really really want the best for people who learn with them.

VeraCrypt : Open Source Encryption Softwareüêßüíª‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£
VeraCrypt is a free open source disk encryption software for Windows, Mac OSX and Linux.‚Å£
‚Å£
Main features:‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Creates a virtual encrypted disk within a file and mounts it as a real disk.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Encrypts an entire partition or storage device such as USB flash drive or hard drive.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Encrypts a partition or drive where Windows is installed (pre-boot authentication).‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Encryption is automatic, real-time(on-the-fly) and transparent.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Parallelization and pipelining allow data to be read and written as fast as if the drive was not encrypted.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Encryption can be hardware-accelerated on modern processors.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Provides plausible deniability, in case an adversary forces you to reveal the password: Hidden volume (steganography) and hidden operating system.‚Å£

‚ú® GATSBY JS ‚ú®

‚á¢ GatsbyJS is a framework which sits on top of ReactJS (which in turn sits on top of JavaScript!) üòÑ
‚á¢ It is a static site generator, which means content is generated as HTML on the client side during build time, allowing for many benefits such as super fast loading time, easier SEO & higher security.
‚á¢ Having said that, there is quite a steep learning curve with Gatsby, but I personally feel that it is worth it! üèî 
‚á¢ Here I‚Äôm working on a blog I built with Gatsby, and the speed really is noticeably much faster than using normal React!
‚á¢ I also enjoy how easily Gatsby ties in with GraphQL, to make fetching data from content management tools such as Contentful much cleaner than when using a traditional REST API‚ÄºÔ∏è
‚á¢ Gatsby 4 is now in Beta, and although I haven‚Äôt tried it myself yet, I‚Äôm excited to see which new features are included! ü§©

üí´ What are your thoughts on GatsbyJS? Do you use it at work or for your personal projects, or do you prefer other alternatives / server side rendering frameworks such as Next.js? üí´

‚ú® THE POWER OF SAYING NO ‚ú®

‚á¢ The other day, someone asked me to help them with a coding part of their business project. I didn‚Äôt have time to do that, yet I felt a horrendous guilt in saying no as I hate to feel as though I‚Äôm letting people down. üòï
‚á¢ It was only when someone close to me pointed out that I tend to overload myself with other people‚Äôs priorities that I fully came to realise the importance of saying no.
‚á¢ ‚ÄúThe difference between successful people and really successful people is that really successful people say no to almost everything‚Äù - Warren Buffett. üí´
‚á¢ Nobody can say yes to everything, and if you are constantly taking pressure off from other people, you are constantly closer to overloading yourself. Saying no might feel painful in the moment, but it‚Äôs more painful to have a burnout later down the line‚ÄºÔ∏è
‚á¢ This is especially tough for women, as there is still the subconscious tendency to assume women should be naturally ‚Äúcaring‚Äù as well as hardworking; therefore more open to helping others.
‚á¢ But as women in a male dominated industry, it‚Äôs essential that we work to let go of this guilt. We can‚Äôt expect to be superhuman; it‚Äôs crucial to protect your brain from being overloaded with stress and preserve energy for your own priories. ‚ò∫Ô∏è‚ú®

‚á¢ Books to read:
The Art of Saying No: How to Stand Your Ground, Reclaim Time and Energy, and Refuse to be Taken for Granted - Damon Zahariades

‚á¢ üí´ Have you ever struggled with saying no? Have your tried to overcome the tendency to accept more than you can handle? If so, how?! I‚Äôd love to hear! üí´

‚ú®FORCING YOURSELF TO READ DOCUMENTATION‚ú®

‚á¢ There are many resources out there for learning about every topic under the sun in regards to software development, but at the end of the day - learning from primary source is always the best way to do it.
‚á¢ Reasons for this include that official documentation will always give you the most up to date guidance, and it is released by the company itself so will have been checked by many employees with specific, specialist knowledge before it hits production, versus secondary sources like YouTube videos which may have only been released by one individual, with no affiliation to the company releasing the technology.
‚á¢ In my opinion, it‚Äôs great to start off with YouTube tutorials, freecodecamp etc., StackOverflow and blogs, but the earlier you get started reading the dreaded documentation, the easier it will become to get into a habit of it long-term.

‚á¢ üí´ What are your opinions of documentation? Do you always check there when you have a problem, or do you end up relying on StackOverflow, blogs & YouTube? üí´

‚ú® COWORKING SPACES VS THE OFFICE ‚ú®

‚á¢ With COVID-19 changing the way we work, many employers now offer a hybrid work system where the office is available to employees a few days per week, while others are offering fully remote roles
‚á¢ I think that the growth of remote roles will in turn lead to more coworking spaces, as people naturally crave human company during the workday!
‚á¢ PROS OF COWORKING SPACES vs the traditional office: These provide an opportunity to meet new people who you might normally never engage with, which can lead to a spike in creativity and encourage new ways of thinking, leading to more innovative ideas and strategies for your business/the business you work for. They also allow you to work in exotic locations whilst providing rooms/types of work spaces to suit different needs, and tend to have a more creative aura than the traditional office. Side note: It can be relaxing to be able to wear what you want to without judgement from managers or colleagues!
‚á¢ CONS OF COWORKING SPACES vs the traditional office: There can be a lack of opportunity to build up solid, lasting relationships as people who spend time in coworking spaces are often remote workers and therefore very mobile. The stable community, routine, permanent private desk space and certain perks that an office offers can‚Äôt easily be replaced by a coworking space. It can also be detrimental to miss out on building friendships with your colleagues, but this can, of course, be managed by video communication and occasional in-person meet-ups!

‚á¢ ‚ÄúHappy International Women‚Äôs Day!

"Women can do whatever they want. There is no limit to what we as women can accomplish" - Michelle Obama.

Working in a male-dominated field, it wouldn‚Äôt be surprising to feel demotivated or intimidated by consistently being the only female in the room. But contrary to what might be expected, the men around me have only encouraged, supported and motivated me in my software development journey and in my aim to help other women and girls forge their own path in the tech industry.

There is, however, still a notable lack of female representation, and the quote "you can't be what you can't see" continues to hold truth for young girls looking to become successful within the tech field. 

Today, the primary focus is to celebrate all of the amazing, hardworking and ambitious female trailblazers who have fought hard to give young girls a role model. But alongside this, I want to celebrate each man who is actively taking a stand to help dismantle glass ceilings and make space for women in the tech industry. Real, lasting change can only be achieved by working together in one camp, and I‚Äôm delighted to see it taking place.‚Äù

We‚Äôve all been there, looking at some awful code written a moron, an absolute idiot who doesn‚Äôt deserve to write code for a living .... only to look at the git commit history to see it was you, 6 months ago ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èüòÇ

Suddenly you are very forgiving, remembering that the task was poorly defined, you had a cold that week and you kept getting interrupted by support tickets ü§í

If it wasn‚Äôt your name on the commit history it‚Äôs unlikely your would change your opinion though, especially if the dev in question isn‚Äôt someone you know.

Remember that you don‚Äôt know the circumstances around which a piece of code was written, it might be convoluted, buggy and a bit rubbish but chances are the developer was trying their best in the moment.

Be charitable with the names you see in your git commit history, they were likely perfectly competent developers and didn‚Äôt write code just to cause you a headache üòâ

What does a good merge/pull request look like? ü§î

There are a few things that you can do to make you fellow coders lives easier when reviewing your merge/pull requests:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Check it yourself first, you‚Äôll be amazed what you catch in the in browser diff tool
2Ô∏è‚É£ Add a meaningful title, including a Jira or task ticket number where possible
3Ô∏è‚É£ Give a small description of what the code does, if it addresses multiple unrelated things don‚Äôt just put ‚Äúvarious/bug fixes‚Äù break them out in bullet points
4Ô∏è‚É£ Include screenshots if the UI has changed - this really helps orientate the reviewer in the application
5Ô∏è‚É£ Explain any areas you are unhappy with or would like some input on, you can either do this in the description or add a comment (Gitlab/Github comment, not in the code) at the line in question asking for their thoughts

Don‚Äôt do this.... üòí

I saw a discussion recently about wether it would be a good idea to add intentional bugs to a pull requests to see if your code reviewers can spot them ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

On the surface it might seem like a good idea, you get to see who is really reading the code and who‚Äôs just rubber stamping pull requests but....

From an team perspective this is terrible, it adds stress to an already hard job (reviewing someone else‚Äôs code) and all for basically no real benefit to the organisation. Something like this, I believe, would have a more negative impact on a team than any slight benefits it could bring.

A side affect of a ‚Äúfake bug‚Äù could be a real bug, the code gets accidentally merged, people spend far longer on code reviews trying to find the bug and people who miss them potentially get punished.

What do you think?
